Most of the time men take the divorce decision and legally file a case for dissolution of the marriage; however, in some cases women also initiate the divorce twice as often as men (Rahman & Koenig, 2008a).
What is understood as the most getting divorced is domestic violence; it affects the everyday lives of married couples struggling in different dimensions of married life. Dhoundiyal (2009) mentioned that a large number of women staying in domestic violence situations were from Bangladesh. Wide range studies differentiated 93% of the women stayed in physical violence, 94% in verbal abuse, 43% in sexual harassment, 55% in financial control, 60% psychological pressure, and 30% after/her other relationship (Rahman & Koenig, 2008b).
According to Sultana (2011), more than 80% of the women keep silence for the domestic violence. More than 65% of divorced women are lean towards post-divorce depression (Allam, 2013; Bajracharya & Perkinson, 2007). Therefore, unbearable domestic violence makes them helpless, consequentially they are going through severe psychological distresses.
